aces becomes daily more complicated with the transnational movement of peoples, ideas, technologies, and cultures. Global capitalism relentlessly alters established ethnographic assumptions about the meaning and importance of where we are and have been. The essays presented here are about letting go, learning and un-learning, transgressing physical, emotional, and intellectual boundaries. They are about personal quests, narrated in distinctive voices, raising particular concerns. Together they contribute significantly to our understanding of how small islands in a vast ocean enable us to see ourselves and the world around us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aIntellectualsxHomes and hauntszOceania. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aFinney, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFirth, Stewart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanlon, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHezel, Francis X., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowe, K. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLal, Brij V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLal, Brij V., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMarshall, Mac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Clive, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMosko, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelson, Hank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOgan, Eugene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeacock, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeter, Joakim Jojo, econtributor.4ctb